<P>
 SEAT BELTS REQUIRED? by Henry Tatnall (Dorrance Publishing: $9.95; 118 pp., 
paperback original). Driving regulations differ surprisingly in the 50 states 
and the District of Columbia: Speed limits range from 65 to 25 m.p.h., and the 
amount of alcohol in the blood stream that constitutes D.U.I. varies from .05% 
to .15% (.02% for those under 18 in Vermont). In Alaska, big-game animals 
killed or wounded in vehicular collisions become the property of the state; 
backing up on a Interstate Highway is illegal in Minnesota, as is playing a 
sound system loud enough to be heard 50 feet away in Oregon. Tatnall's modest 
guide offers anyone planning a cross-country drive an easy way to avoid 
tickets. 
