1048 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLUGGING THE LEAK; CAMPUS SPRING WATER SEEN AS UNTAPPED RESOURCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAN CRAY, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 By the time you finish reading this story, 39 gallons of potentially drinkable 
water will have flowed from the campus of University High School into the 
gutters -- but that's just a drop in the bucket. 
</P>
<P>
 Last month, 580,000 gallons dribbled away at the West Los Angeles school; last 
year, 7.3 million gallons were wasted. In the week after the Northridge 
earthquake, when water problems abounded on the Westside, an estimated 140,000 
gallons were lost. 
</P>
<P>
 And that's not to mention the 43.8 million gallons lost during the six years 
of drought that ended last winter. 
</P>
<P>
 The source of all of these lost gallons: natural springs on the northern side 
of University High. One spring feeds into a charming man-made waterfall at the 
northwest corner of the soccer field. The other supplies a pair of ponds in the 
agricultural portion of the campus, between Wilshire and Santa Monica 
boulevards, just west of the San Diego Freeway. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 In the end, however, all of the water winds up in the storm drains that lead 
to Santa Monica Bay. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's all going down the drain today, just as it did every day of the 
(post-earthquake) crisis," said Jon Shaughnessy, executive director of the 
fledgling West Los Angeles Chamber of Commerce, which organized in September. 
"We basically have a leak that needs fixing, but no one has spent the time and 
money to make sure this is a usable source of water in a crisis." 
</P>
<P>
 As a result, the West Los Angeles Chamber has formed a disaster preparedness 
committee that will make development of the springs one of its priorities. 
</P>
<P>
 The question, however, is whether businesses will pony up the necessary cash. 
Shaughnessy said preliminary estimates of the cost of installing equipment to 
pump the spring water into a holding tank run about $20,000. Thus far, no one 
has stepped forward with financial commitments. 
</P>
<P>
 "The main project is to get financial support to cap the springs off," 
Shaughnessy said. "A lot has to do with how much of the work we can have done 
pro bono." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 In 1991, when a West Los Angeles community organization applied for federal 
funding under the Urban Forestry and Gardening Grants program to reclaim the 
water from the springs, the cost was estimated at $54,000, not including labor. 
The grant request was rejected. 
</P>
<P>
 "We never had much information, so we just kind of ball-parked some numbers," 
said Raymond Scott of RS Engineering, the Santa Monica development firm that 
provided this estimate. "No one ever gave us a real plan. Someone just got a 
bug for the idea and gave us a call." 
</P>
<P>
 Considering the colorful history of the springs -- the Tongva Indians had a 
village at the site 200 years ago -- it is perhaps surprising that they have 
never been thoroughly studied. 
</P>
<P>
 Indeed, the only measurement of their flow rate was by a volunteer who timed 
how long it took to fill up a pail and figured that 20,000 gallons bubble forth 
each day. The lack of solid information, however, makes an accurate estimate of 
development costs a near impossibility. 
</P>
<P>
 "You could spend about anything on something like this," Scott said. "It's a 
shame to have it go to waste, but there's no verified supply and we don't 
really know if (the water) is reclaimable. Then you'll need a reservoir, a pump 
to get it to the tank. (You'll need to) decide how many gallons you want to 
keep in reserve at all times. Do you want to employ it every day? Can it be 
used for irrigation, or for the flush toilets at the school? There are so many 
variables because nobody's really done anything with it." 
</P>
<P>
 At one point, the Los Angeles Department of Water & Power conducted an 
informal feasibility study of the springs but chose not to pursue the matter. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've looked at it from a supply perspective, and we didn't think it was 
worth the while," said Peter Kavounas, a DWP hydrologic engineer. "It just 
didn't seem like there was much water to be had, and what there was had enough 
quality problems that it would need treatment to make it potable. It wasn't 
cost-effective, because we have to live up to national health standards. If 
(the West Los Angeles Chamber) doesn't have to meet national health standards, 
it might be more feasible for them than it was for us." 
</P>
<P>
 Kavounas, who has not seen the springs, said DWP research suggests that the 
water contains a lot of iron. This is typical of springs that form when 
rainwater in nearby mountains percolates into the ground and resurfaces after 
passing through formations containing iron and other minerals. 
</P>
<P>
 "What it would take (to tap the springs) is to be in a different part of the 
country," he contends. "In Southern California, when it rains it pours. You 
never really have the less-intense rains that go on for days at a time. That 
means the reservoirs it takes to capture such large, sudden rainwater amounts 
have to be very big facilities, and that's very costly." 
</P>
<P>
 Kavounas said the DWP has no claim to the water rights, which would fall to 
the owner of the property -- the Los Angeles Unified School District. 
</P>
<P>
 Many have suggested that the district could use the springs for irrigation and 
thus cut down on filtering expenses and the number of gallons it purchases from 
the DWP. The district's department of architectural engineering reportedly 
studied the matter two years ago, but its deputy director, Robert Donald, did 
not return phone inquiries. 
</P>
<P>
 Nancy Rene, assistant principal at University High, said experience indicates 
that an on-campus water source might help the school save money. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't know what the district is paying for irrigation, but I know that from 
time to time it has been very expensive," she said. "We've got a large campus, 
and right now we're not able to irrigate every single area on campus. If we 
could use this supply of water, I think it would help." 
</P>
<P>
 Ideally, Rene would like to see the water used as an emergency supply for the 
school's 2,000 students and staff members. Shaughnessy of the West Los Angeles 
Chamber had the same thought. 
</P>
<P>
 "On Jan. 17, when the National Guard asked if they could put a hose up and get 
some water and the answer had to be no, their response was, 'Thanks anyway,' " 
he said. "Right now it's easier to truck it in from Tehachapi than it is to 
pick it up in a plastic bucket, and we don't want that to be the case when the 
next quake hits." 
</P>
</TEXT>
