<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE TENTATIVELY OKS TERM-LIMITS PLAN; POLITICS: CITY WANTS TO JOIN LAGUNA 
NIGUEL IN URGING LEGISLATORS TO GRANT GENERAL-LAW CITIES THE POWER TO RESTRICT 
LENGTH OF SERVICE FOR COUNCIL MEMBERS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN MILLER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Orange is poised to become the county's second city to call for legislation 
that would allow general law cities to establish term limits for their city 
councils. 
</P>
<P>
 Under state law, only cities with charters can legally set term limits. Voters 
in such chartered cities as Santa Ana and Anaheim have approved term limits for 
their councils. So-called general law cities, usually smaller in population, do 
not have the authority to enact term limits. 
</P>
<P>
 Orange wants to join Laguna Niguel in pressuring state legislators to grant 
general law cities the power to impose term limits on council members. Laguna 
Niguel passed a term-limits measure in February. On a 5-0 vote Tuesday, the 
Orange City Council tentatively approved a similar resolution. 
</P>
<P>
 Orange Councilman Mike Spurgeon, a staunch advocate of term limits, said 
council members should be restricted to two terms of four years, while a mayor 
should be held to three two-year terms. According to the proposal, a person 
could serve on the City Council, and also as mayor, before being ineligible to 
run again. 
</P>
<P>
 "That gives somebody 14 years to do what they want to do if they plan it 
right," said Spurgeon, who introduced the matter Tuesday afternoon. "If they 
can't do it in that time, there are plenty of other people waiting to do it 
with fresh perspective." 
</P>
<P>
 Two years ago, in a non-binding "advisory" election, 86% of Orange voters cast 
ballots to establish term limits on the City Council. 
</P>
<P>
 In spite of the advisory election, Orange voters continue to reelect their 
city officials beyond what proposed term limits would allow. Mayor Gene Beyer 
has served 2 1/2 terms as a council member and, most recently, two terms as 
mayor. Fred Barrera has been on the council since 1976. 
</P>
<P>
 Spurgeon said that because of the election results, he feels a moral 
obligation to step down when his two terms on the council are up -- regardless 
of whether a term limit law has been passed. Spurgeon was appointed to the 
council in 1990 and was elected to the body in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA031394-0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 022376 </DOCID>
