<HEADLINE>
<P>
TENNIS ROUNDUP; PETCHEY DEFEATED BY AGASSI 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Andre Agassi, still trying to rebound from a dismal year that included wrist 
surgery and a breakup with his coach, defeated Britain's Mark Petchey, 6-2, 
4-6, 6-4, in his opening match at the Lipton Championships on Saturday at Key 
Biscayne, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was really a nightmare year for me," Agassi said. 
</P>
<P>
 He skipped the Australian Open in January while recuperating from surgery, won 
at Scottsdale, Ariz., last month and then was eliminated in the second round at 
Indian Wells. 
</P>
<P>
 "My game is coming along at an incredible pace right now," Agassi said. "I 
feel great about where I am. There's no question in my mind that I'm going to 
get better and better every match I play." 
</P>
<P>
 No. 2 Stefan Edberg, No. 3 Sergi Brugera, No. 5 Goran Ivanisevic and No. 6 
Michael Chang also won their opening matches. 
</P>
<P>
 MaliVai Washington, a finalist last year, was eliminated by Jared Palmer, 6-3, 
7-6 (8-6). 
</P>
<P>
 Advancing in women's play were top-seeded Steffi Graf, No. 2 Arantxa Sanchez 
Vicario and No. 3 Gabriela Sabatini. 
</P>
<P>
 Sixth-seeded Mary Joe Fernandez withdrew before her match because of illness. 
No. 11 Helena Sukova lost, 6-3, 6-4, to Radka Zrubakova of Slovakia, ranked 
142nd in the world. 
</P>
<P>
 Agassi will next play Boris Becker, a 3-6, 6-4, 6-0 winner over Nicklas Kulti 
of Sweden. Becker is coached by Nick Bollettieri, who ended a longtime 
relationship with Agassi last summer. 
</P>
<P>
 "It'll be weird seeing Nick in another box. In some ways, it'll feel good," 
said Agassi, ranked 31st in the world. "I lost a lot of respect for him, and 
it's going to take time for me to get over that." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Lars Rehmann of Germany and Sweden's Magnus Larsson advanced to the final of 
the Zaragoza Open in Spain. Larsson, seeded fourth, defeated countryman Anders 
Jarryd, 6-4, 4-6, 6-2, and the unseeded Rehmann, ranked No. 310 in the world, 
defeated Tomas Nydahl of Sweden, 7-5, 6-4. 
</P>
