<HEADLINE>
<P>
SECURING YOUR HOME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CAROL TICE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 There are a great number of publications and videos available to help 
homeowners learn more about how to retrofit their foundations. Many were 
created after the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake. Here's a selection of 
publications and videos of particular interest to homeowner: PUBLICATIONS 
</P>
<P>
 "Earthquake Safe: A Hazard Reduction Manual for Homes" by David Benaroya 
Helfant (Builders Booksource, 1817 4th St., Berkeley, Calif. 94710; (510) 
845-6874). Written by an engineer, this 56-page book is packed with details and 
diagrams on foundation retrofitting. Available for $9.44 including shipping and 
tax. 
</P>
<P>
 "The Homeowner's Guide to Earthquake Safety" by the California Seismic Safety 
Commission. This large-format booklet provides homeowners with simple 
information about the questions they need to answer when selling their pre-1960 
home, and remedies to strengthen their foundation. Also lists many other 
publications. $6.81 from the California Assn. of Realtors, 525 S. Virgil Ave., 
L.A. 90020 (213) 739-8200. 
</P>
<P>
 "Introduction to Earthquake Retrofitting" by the Builder Education Center (812 
Page St., Berkeley, Calif. 94710; (510) 525-7610). An 80-page guide to the 
tools and techniques needed for basic retrofitting project, illustrated with 60 
photos. Very do-it-yourselfer oriented. $13.77 including tax, shipping. 
</P>
<P>
 "Peace of Mind in Earthquake Country" by Peter I. Yanev (Chronicle Books, 275 
5th St., San Francisco, Calif. 94103; (415) 777-7240). This book provides such 
a thorough education on earthquakes' causes and effects that it doesn't even 
get to retrofitting until Chapter 7. With recent interest, this 218 page-book 
should be available at local bookstores. It's list-priced at $14.95. 
</P>
<P>
 "Strengthening Wood Frame Houses for Earthquake Safety" by the Bay Area 
Regional Earthquake Preparedness Project. This 32-page booklet includes photos, 
diagrams and estimates of what each job should cost the homeowner. Available 
for $6 total from the Assn. of Bay Area Governments, P.O. Box 2050, Oakland, 
Calif. 94604; (510) 464-7900. VIDEOS 
</P>
<P>
 All these videos are roughly a half-hour, and all provide good information -- 
but they all make it look easy by demonstrating the work in enormous, 
basement-like areas. Be warned that your home is probably much more cramped 
underneath. Also, all three were produced in the Bay Area, so remember code 
specifications for your house may be slightly different. 
</P>
<P>
 "An Ounce of Prevention: Strengthening Your Wood Frame House for Earthquake 
Safety" by the Bay Area Earthquake Preparedness Project. Allan Lindh of the 
U.S. Geological survey hosts this show, which features a thorough seismic 
survey section and good step-by-step instructions. Comes with 12-page checklist 
of tools and materials. It's $16.09 total from the Assn. of Bay Area 
Governments, P.O. Box 2050, Oakland, Calif. 94604; (510) 464-7900. 
</P>
<P>
 "Bolt It Down: The Homeowners Guide to Earthquake Protection." Put together by 
the International Conference of Building Officials and the Los Angeles County 
Department of Public Works. A Seismic Safety Commission official takes you 
through the basic foundation retrofitting steps. Comes with a 40-page 
information booklet; $10.50 plus tax (includes shipping and handling). Order by 
calling (310) 692-4226. 
</P>
<P>
 "Earthquake: Home Safe Home." Funded by sympathetic Japanese Rotarians after 
the Loma Prieta earthquake, and produced by TV station KCSM. In this tape Tony 
DeMascole of the Earthquake Engineering Research Institute takes you through 
the retrofitting steps. Send $24.60 to Earthquake, KCSM, 1700 W. Hillsdale 
Blvd., San Mateo, Calif. 94402 or call (415) 574-6586. FINANCIAL HELP FOR 
RETROFITTING 
</P>
<P>
 Recognizing the cost-effectiveness of securing foundations before an 
earthquake, FEMA has established a grant program to help homeowners bolt their 
foundations, brace cripple walls, anchor mobile homes and strap chimneys. 
</P>
<P>
 The repair program is available only for owner-occupied primary residences 
affected by the earthquake and the maximum grant is $10,000. Interested 
homeowners should call FEMA at (800) 525-0321. CAROL TICE 
</P>
</TEXT>
