<HEADLINE>
<P>
LEADER OF CALI CARTEL TURNS HIMSELF IN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A leader of the world's biggest cocaine-trafficking gang surrendered Saturday 
following months of negotiations between his lawyers and authorities. 
</P>
<P>
 The surrender of Cali cartel leader Julio Fabio Urdinola came 100 days after 
authorities killed Pablo Escobar, the boss of the rival Medellin cartel. 
</P>
<P>
 But the government used different strategies in netting the two: a military 
operation against Escobar and talks and offers of leniency for the Cali 
leaders. 
</P>
<P>
 A broadcast by the Cripton TV news station showed Urdinola pulling up in a 
station wagon to a maximum-security penitentiary in Palmira, 18 miles east of 
Cali, and going inside. 
</P>
<P>
 Under a penal code enacted late last year, traffickers who surrender, disclose 
their operations and turn their illicit gains over to the state can win 
leniency. 
</P>
